1226
01:17:59,203 --> 01:18:02,100
- One more song.
- No, please, it's so late.

1227
01:18:02,201 --> 01:18:04,200
One more song, just one more.

1228
01:18:08,201 --> 01:18:10,800
- Gee, Betsy, you were terrific.
- Oh, thanks.

1229
01:18:11,701 --> 01:18:15,000
- Let's get out of here, huh?
- Sure.

1230
01:18:15,031 --> 01:18:17,400
I want to show you something
right here in New York...

1231
01:18:17,431 --> 01:18:19,880
...that millions of people
never see in their whole lifetime.

1232
01:18:19,900 --> 01:18:20,900
What?

1233
01:18:20,920 --> 01:18:22,900
A horse.
Come on.

1234
01:18:30,001 --> 01:18:32,140
You don't suppose something
will happen...

1235
01:18:32,141 --> 01:18:34,150
...that'll keep you from going
home tomorrow?

1236
01:18:34,801 --> 01:18:36,700
No, we have our tickets.

1237
01:18:37,901 --> 01:18:40,580
Are you sure it's all right
for you to stay out this late?

1238
01:18:40,600 --> 01:18:43,200
You know, it's getting dawn.

1239
01:18:43,601 --> 01:18:46,000
I'd stay out even if it wasn't all right.

1240
01:18:46,001 --> 01:18:48,301
Well, I wouldn't let you. Your mother
expects me to take care of you.

1241
01:18:49,672 --> 01:18:51,600
It gives me the nicest feeling.

1242
01:18:53,301 --> 01:18:57,000
You know, I...
I wish I wasn't leaving New York.

1243
01:18:58,201 --> 01:19:01,300
Oh, we can write to each other.

1244
01:19:01,401 --> 01:19:02,601
Yeah.

1245
01:19:03,602 --> 01:19:07,802
And every time I get a letter I'll pretend
you're sending me gardenias.

1246
01:19:08,203 --> 01:19:09,500
Like these.

1247
01:19:09,501 --> 01:19:13,301
Oh... I'm getting too old
for pretending.

1248
01:19:14,702 --> 01:19:16,602
I will send you gardenias.

1249
01:19:16,993 --> 01:19:20,703
Only not right away on account of that
allowance trouble that I told you about.

1250
01:19:21,404 --> 01:19:24,670
- Are you cold?
- No, I'm not cold. It's...

1251
01:19:25,471 --> 01:19:27,271
...it's just like Indian summer.

1252
01:19:29,000 --> 01:19:30,100
You know...

1253
01:19:30,901 --> 01:19:34,280
You know, you've changed a lot since
the last time you were in Carvel.

1254
01:19:34,310 --> 01:19:37,881
- I have?
- Yeah, you're more grown up...

1255
01:19:38,682 --> 01:19:41,882
Gee, I completely almost forgot
how swell you were.

1256
01:19:45,483 --> 01:19:48,500
Maybe I wasn't as swell
when I was in Carvel...

1257
01:19:49,401 --> 01:19:51,350
Or maybe you just didn't notice.

1258
01:19:55,381 --> 01:19:57,651
One thing about me
hasn't changed though.

1259
01:19:59,000 --> 01:20:02,252
No boy has ever kissed me yet.

1260
01:20:04,553 --> 01:20:08,153
You know, I was sitting here
thinking that I...

1261
01:20:08,854 --> 01:20:11,754
I wanted to...
I wanted to kiss you...

1262
01:20:13,255 --> 01:20:17,700
Then when I think that I do,
then I'm afraid that I don't.

1263
01:20:18,201 --> 01:20:19,500
Don't want to?

1264
01:20:19,521 --> 01:20:23,400
Sometimes wanting to and not wanting to
is better than wanting to.

1265
01:20:25,101 --> 01:20:29,999
I know... I knew you were thinking
about kissing me.

1266
01:20:31,200 --> 01:20:35,400
And I was just as afraid you would
as much as I was afraid you wouldn't.

1267
01:20:36,601 --> 01:20:41,001
Gosh, this is much too important
to be monkeying around with.

1268
01:20:42,802 --> 01:20:44,602
I'll remember that too.

1269
01:20:45,203 --> 01:20:48,000
Till we can see each other again.

1270
01:20:50,000 --> 01:20:51,201
Betsy,

1271
01:20:51,802 --> 01:20:53,702
I'll come back someday.

1272
01:20:56,000 --> 01:20:57,903
If you mean that...

1273
01:20:58,704 --> 01:21:03,104
...maybe you'd better kiss me
even if we both don't want to.

1274
01:21:11,205 --> 01:21:12,605
Someday.

1275
01:21:14,000 --> 01:21:17,706
Betsy, hey...

1276
01:21:17,907 --> 01:21:19,607
Don't cry.

1277
01:21:22,908 --> 01:21:24,508
I know why you're crying.

1278
01:21:25,609 --> 01:21:27,409
You're crying because...

1279
01:21:28,010 --> 01:21:29,910
Because I kissed you.

1280
01:21:32,411 --> 01:21:35,700
It isn't that glamourous to cry.

1281
01:21:38,201 --> 01:21:42,501
It's funny. When a girl cries
because you like her...

1282
01:21:43,802 --> 01:21:47,800
why, even when her nose is shiny
she's glamourous.

1283
01:21:48,201 --> 01:21:50,501
Oh, boy, that's what I call glamour.

1284
01:21:52,102 --> 01:21:53,602
I'll bet you...

1285
01:21:53,603 --> 01:21:57,400
I'll bet your Polly Benedict
couldn't be glamourous with a shiny nose.

1286
01:21:57,401 --> 01:22:02,101
Polly Benedict? Just you wait
until I get back to Carvel.

1287
01:22:13,002 --> 01:22:16,702
New York is wonderful,
but it's always good to get home.

1288
01:22:16,703 --> 01:22:18,570
Excuse me, everybody.
I've got to fix my hair.

1289
01:22:18,591 --> 01:22:21,900
Excuse me, too, I've got a couple
of predatory insects to destroy.

1290
01:22:21,921 --> 01:22:25,330
Save me a trip, will you, son?
Drop Francis off at the orphanage.

1291
01:22:25,341 --> 01:22:28,100
Oh, Dad, I'm too big to be
carting around babies.

1292
01:22:28,101 --> 01:22:30,000
Too big for your britches?

1293
01:22:31,501 --> 01:22:33,000
I'm sorry.

1294
01:22:33,021 --> 01:22:36,301
Gosh, bub, what a lot of grief you're
gonna go through before you're my age.

1295
01:22:38,402 --> 01:22:41,202
James, I smell coffee.

1296
01:22:41,203 --> 01:22:43,203
Now, now, Mother, that's...

1297
01:22:47,004 --> 01:22:48,300
Wasn't I silly to worry?

1298
01:22:48,301 --> 01:22:51,001
I just remembered what I told Andy
was to cancel the milk.

1299
01:22:51,032 --> 01:22:55,000
Don't worry about the milk. I personally
told the milkman not to leave any.

1300
01:23:01,901 --> 01:23:05,400
Hello, Polly? Have you seen your
advanced copy of the Olympian?

1301
01:23:05,401 --> 01:23:07,001
No, I haven't yet.

1302
01:23:07,002 --> 01:23:09,852
But it's here. I'll look at it right away.
Hold the wire.

1303
01:23:25,453 --> 01:23:26,800
I saw it!

1304
01:23:27,101 --> 01:23:29,001
I... I...

1305
01:23:29,002 --> 01:23:31,202
But how could it ever have happened?

1306
01:23:31,403 --> 01:23:33,703
What are we going to do?

1307
01:23:33,999 --> 01:23:36,104
Listen, I'll meet you
at the school right away.

1308
01:23:46,705 --> 01:23:49,705
Of course Andy had the cover changed,
but how did he dare?

1309
01:23:49,776 --> 01:23:53,606
Oh, Beezy, he did know that girl.
What awful idiots we've been.

1310
01:23:53,657 --> 01:23:55,480
Cynthia Potter warned me.

1311
01:23:55,500 --> 01:23:57,450
Andy kissed her the first time
he took her out.

1312
01:23:57,471 --> 01:24:00,051
I should have known better
than to trifle with a man like Andy.

1313
01:24:00,072 --> 01:24:04,352
Beezy, maybe he's been secretly married
to that Daphne Fowler all the time.

1314
01:24:12,653 --> 01:24:15,353
Andy Hardy, whose baby is that?

1315
01:24:16,299 --> 01:24:21,654
I remember you, sister. You're the little
girl that failed in geometry.

1316
01:24:22,155 --> 01:24:24,950
It was to protect this innocent babe's
future that we went to New York.

1317
01:24:24,981 --> 01:24:25,971
What?

1318
01:24:26,472 --> 01:24:28,572
Oh, the orphanage.

1319
01:24:28,593 --> 01:24:32,703
Polly, look. I thought I was dreaming
but they're all the same.

1320
01:24:32,704 --> 01:24:35,904
Of course, you printed up the story and I
supplied you with an exclusive cover.

1321
01:24:35,935 --> 01:24:37,600
And it's not faked either.

1322
01:24:37,631 --> 01:24:40,300
I trust that the younger generation
of this town...

1323
01:24:40,321 --> 01:24:42,000
...has learned to respect its elders.

1324
01:24:42,021 --> 01:24:45,300
I'm sorry, Andy.
I take back everything I said.

1325
01:24:45,341 --> 01:24:47,000
I'll apologize in writing.

1326
01:24:47,031 --> 01:24:49,800
Not necessary at all, bub,
you're just too big for your britches.

1327
01:24:49,821 --> 01:24:52,201
Take Francis back
to the orphanage for me.

1328
01:24:52,232 --> 01:24:54,400
Yes, sir...
I mean, yes, Andy.

1329
01:24:55,001 --> 01:24:57,801
Come on. You and me we'll stop
at Cynthia Potter's.

1330
01:24:57,842 --> 01:25:00,000
She's just crazy about babies.

1331
01:25:00,021 --> 01:25:02,000
You said a mouthful, toots.

1332
01:25:04,501 --> 01:25:07,401
So Daphne Fowler was in love
with you all the time.

1333
01:25:07,432 --> 01:25:08,900
Well, there's our picture there.

1334
01:25:08,921 --> 01:25:12,141
Society's Number One Glamour Girl
trying to coax me for a smile.

1335
01:25:12,762 --> 01:25:16,442
Swell girl, Daph.
Sort of a.. adolescent Cleopatra.

1336
01:25:16,743 --> 01:25:20,743
- Perhaps you are too mature for me.
- No doubt, no doubt.

1337
01:25:21,244 --> 01:25:23,744
But you know, Polly, when I was
in New York I was thinking.

1338
01:25:23,765 --> 01:25:27,885
Sophisticated girls, they make you
appreciate old-fashioned girls.

1339
01:25:28,386 --> 01:25:31,486
You know, the type that starts to cry
when you kiss them.

1340
01:25:32,787 --> 01:25:36,100
Are... are you engaged
to Daphne Fowler?

1341
01:25:36,101 --> 01:25:39,999
Daphne? Oh, no.
Just another milestone in my career.

1342
01:25:40,900 --> 01:25:44,500
You know, Polly. You used to be
a sweet, unaffected little child.

1343
01:25:44,701 --> 01:25:48,100
And I always thought that you
kind of looked up to me.

1344
01:25:48,351 --> 01:25:51,801
I do, Andy.
I think...

1345
01:25:51,902 --> 01:25:55,000
I think I should cry right now
if you were to kiss me.

1346
01:25:55,100 --> 01:26:00,500
That's a good idea. But of course
you don't want to go to extremes.

1347
01:26:01,301 --> 01:26:04,000
When you kiss a girl,
as I was telling Betsy,

1348
01:26:04,041 --> 01:26:08,500
- Betsy!
- Uh, why, It slipped... it slipped out.

1349
01:26:09,501 --> 01:26:12,601
Can I help it
if I have irresistible charm?

1350
01:26:12,622 --> 01:26:14,702
That's not charm. That's polygamy.

1351
01:26:14,723 --> 01:26:17,703
But, oh, Andy,
how we women love it.

1352
01:26:39,704 --> 01:26:42,180
- James, it's lovely.
- You really like it?

1353
01:26:42,200 --> 01:26:43,730
It's beautiful.

1354
01:26:43,750 --> 01:26:47,182
And since you want us to end up
in the poor house, I'll keep it...

1355
01:26:48,183 --> 01:26:51,100
James, you're the best husband
that ever lived.

1356
01:27:05,401 --> 01:27:08,999
Gosh, how one's women
do mount up.

